            <!-- Why This Calculator Matters -->
            <section id="why-matters" class="article-section">
                <h2 class="section-title"><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Why This Calculator Matters</h2>

                <p>Most return calculators are generic. This one is built specifically for <strong>Bro Billionaire stocks</strong>—the high-conviction, high-volatility tech names that billionaires bet on.</p>

                <h3 class="subsection-title">1. Reality Check on Past Returns</h3>
                <p>You'll see exactly what you would have made (or lost) buying Nvidia at $100 in 2020, Tesla at $200 in 2019, or Palantir at $10 in 2020. This stops you from fantasizing about "what if" and shows you what actually happened.</p>

                <h3 class="subsection-title">2. Currency Adjusted for Indian Investors</h3>
                <p>If you're an Indian investor buying US stocks, your returns aren't just stock performance—USD-INR movements matter. If USD strengthens 10% against INR, you get a 10% bonus. This calculator factors that in.</p>

                <h3 class="subsection-title">3. Dividend Reinvestment Impact</h3>
                <p>Apple and Microsoft pay dividends. Reinvesting those dividends quarterly adds 1-2% annually to your CAGR. Over 10 years, that's 10-20% extra wealth. Most calculators ignore dividends—this one doesn't.</p>

                <h3 class="subsection-title">4. Compare vs Safe Alternatives</h3>
                <p>You'll see how your Bro Billionaire stocks performed vs S&P 500 (US index) and Nifty 50 (India index). This shows whether the extra risk was worth it. Spoiler: for the last 5 years, Bro Billionaire stocks crushed indices.</p>

                <div class="quote-box">
                    <p>"The biggest risk is not taking enough risk. In a world that's changing quickly, the only strategy guaranteed to fail is not taking risks."</p>
                    <span class="quote-author">— Mark Zuckerberg, Meta CEO</span>
                </div>
            </section>

